    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You have hit on a critical flaw in residual institutional practices: when \"rigor\" is defined solely by prescriptive standards, it explicitly marginalizes valid intellectual contributions from speakers of dialects like AAVE. This creates a systemic bias where the流露 of genius or complex reasoning is punished until it is translated into an editorially sanctioned form, effectively treating cultural heritage as a deficit rather than a recognized mode of thought. While linguists argue that this distinction is merely dialectal, the real-world consequences of adhering to such rigid \"competence\" rubrics do reinforce the idea that certain cognitive approaches are inferior, actively zoning out Black voices from the academy despite their undeniable logical and analytical power. Thus, true scholarly integrity lies in adapting our grading criteria to recognize diverse forms of expression as equally rigorous once the discourse has been accurately translated into academic communication.",
